s of gender, chronicling deindustrialization’s disproportionate impact on women and women’s leading roles in movements for social change. Concluding with a set of essays on black culture and consumption, this volume fully realizes its goal of linking local transformations with the national and global processes that affect urban class and race relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRacismzUnited States. 0aUrban African AmericansxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ablack, city, historical, academic, scholarly, history, wwii, wartime, war, postwar, migration, immigration, race, racism, racial, class, discrimination, america, american, united states, usa, western world, segregation, industrial, industrialization, work, workforce, labor, jobs, relationships, activism, social studies, change, ethnic, 20th century, civil rights, community, culture.1 aBrown, Eric S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamarillo, Albert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Karl Ellis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusmer, Kenneth L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusmer, Kenneth L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevenstein, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcallister, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM